        </div>
        
        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 1 — Merge Sort Overview

            Merge Sort is a **divide and conquer** sorting algorithm.

            It works by:
            1. Dividing the list into smaller parts
            2. Sorting each part
            3. Merging the sorted parts together

            Example list:

            8 3 5 2 9 1 6

            ####T(n) = 2T(n/2) + n####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[List]
              A-->B[Divide]
              A-->C[Divide]
              B-->D[Merge]
              C-->D;
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 2 — Divide Step

            Merge Sort first **splits the list into two halves**.

            Example:

            8 3 5 2 9 1 6 4

            Becomes:

            8 3 5 2  
            9 1 6 4

            ####n → n/2 + n/2####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[8 3 5 2 9 1 6 4]
              A-->B[8 3 5 2]
              A-->C[9 1 6 4];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 3 — Recursive Division

            Each half is divided again.

            8 3 5 2 becomes:

            8 3  
            5 2

            ####log_2(n) levels####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[8 3 5 2]
              A-->B[8 3]
              A-->C[5 2];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 4 — Base Case

            Division continues until lists contain **only one element**.

            Single-element lists are already sorted.

            Example:

            8  
            3  
            5  
            2

            ####T(1) = 1####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[8 3]
              A-->B[8]
              A-->C[3];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 5 — Merge Step Idea

            Sorted lists are merged together.

            Example:

            3 8  
            2 5

            After merging:

            2 3 5 8

            ####n comparisons per level####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[3 8]
              B[2 5]
              A-->C[Merge]
              B-->C
              C-->D[2 3 5 8];
            /mermaid
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 6 — Comparing Elements

            During merging:

            - Compare the first elements
            - Move the smallest element
            - Continue until finished

            Example:

            3 8  
            2 5

            Result starts with:

            2 → 3 → 5 → 8

            ####O(n) merge cost####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[3]
              B[2]
              A-->C[Compare]
              B-->C
              C-->D[2 first];
            /mermaid
            </script>


          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 7 — Full Merge Process

            Example list:

            8 3 5 2

            Split:

            8 3 | 5 2

            Sorted halves:

            3 8 | 2 5

            Final merge:

            2 3 5 8

            ####Total levels = log_2(n)####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[8 3 5 2]
              A-->B[8 3]
              A-->C[5 2]
              B-->D[3 8]
              C-->E[2 5]
              D-->F[2 3 5 8]
              E-->F;
            /mermaid
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 8 — Time Complexity

            Merge Sort always runs in:

            ####O(n log n)####

            Because:

            - There are ####log_2(n)#### levels
            - Each level processes ####n#### elements

            ####n × log_2(n)####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[n]
              A-->B[n]
              A-->C[n]
              B-->D[n]
              C-->E[n];
            /mermaid
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 9 — Advantages and Disadvantages

            Advantages:

            - Very fast for large datasets
            - Guaranteed ####O(n log n)####
            - Stable sorting algorithm

            Disadvantages:

            - Requires extra memory
            - More complex than simple sorts

            ####Space = O(n)####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Merge Sort]
              A-->B[Fast]
              A-->C[Stable]
              A-->D[Extra Memory];
            /mermaid
            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Slide 10 — Merge Sort Algorithm

            Pseudocode:

            1. Split the list
            2. Sort left half
            3. Sort right half
            4. Merge halves

            ####MergeSort(n) = Merge(MergeSort(left), MergeSort(right))####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Start]
              A-->B[Split]
              B-->C[Sort Left]
              B-->D[Sort Right]
              C-->E[Merge]
              D-->E
              E-->F[Sorted List];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Exercise — Implement Merge Sort

            In this exercise you will implement the **Merge Sort** algorithm.

            Merge Sort uses a **divide and conquer** approach:

            1. Divide the list into two halves
            2. Recursively sort both halves
            3. Merge the sorted halves into one sorted list

            Example input:

            8 3 5 2 9 1 6

            Expected output:

            1 2 3 5 6 8 9

            Steps to implement:

            1. Create a function `merge_sort(list)`
            2. If the list has **one element or less**, return the list
            3. Divide the list into two halves
            4. Recursively call `merge_sort()` on both halves
            5. Create a function `merge(left, right)`
            6. Compare elements from both lists
            7. Build a new sorted list
            8. Return the merged list

            ####T(n) = 2T(n/2) + n####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Unsorted List]
              A-->B[Split]
              A-->C[Split]
              B-->D[Merge]
              C-->D;
            /mermaid

            spoiler
            ```
            def merge(left, right):
                result = []
                i = 0
                j = 0

                while i < len(left) and j < len(right):
                    if left[i] <= right[j]:
                        result.append(left[i])
                        i += 1
                    else:
                        result.append(right[j])
                        j += 1

                # Add remaining elements
                while i < len(left):
                    result.append(left[i])
                    i += 1

                while j < len(right):
                    result.append(right[j])
                    j += 1

                return result

            def merge_sort(arr):
                # Base case
                if len(arr) <= 1:
                    return arr

                # Divide
                middle = len(arr) // 2
                left = arr[:middle]
                right = arr[middle:]

                # Conquer
                left_sorted = merge_sort(left)
                right_sorted = merge_sort(right)

                # Merge
                return merge(left_sorted, right_sorted)

            numbers = [8, 3, 5, 2, 9, 1, 6]

            sorted_numbers = merge_sort(numbers)

            print(sorted_numbers)
            ```
            /spoiler
            </script>
